SIMPLE: dotage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dotage
<hw>Do"tage</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Dote</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Feebleness or imbecility of
understanding or mind, particularly in old age; the childishness of old
age; senility; <as>as, a venerable man, now in his
<ex>dotage</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Capable of distinguishing between the infancy and the
<qex>dotage</qex> of Greek literature.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Foolish utterance; drivel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sapless <qex>dotages</qex> of old Paris and Salamanca.</q>
<rj><qau> Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Excessive fondness; weak and foolish
affection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>dotage</qex> of the nation on presbytery.</q> <rj><qau>
Bp. Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dotal</ent>⟦br⟧
